{
  "texts": [
    "This is possible by virtue of a notion of rigidity associated with symmetries which produces simple mathematical invariants for complicated QFT observables, and such invariants can often be calculated by going to weakly-coupled corners in the parameter space.",
    "These invariants encode finer features of symmetries, such as the 't Hooft anomaly for a symmetry group G, and a thorough examination of such invariants can greatly strengthen the predictions from symmetries on the QFT dynamics.",
    "It is well known that a universal and elegant way to probe such invariants of symmetry is to JHEP03(2024)127 couple the QFT to background gauge fields; the 't Hooft anomalies are then obstructions to gauging, which corresponds to promoting these gauge fields to become dynamical while satisfying the basic axioms of QFT.",
    "When the symmetry G of a QFT T is anomaly free, gauging G produces another healthy QFT T /G, and many known QFTs are generated this way.",
    "Various different parts of the QFT theory space are then connected by gauging."
  ]
}